Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chisholm","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Chisholme near Hawick in southern Scotland, which derives its name from Old English <i>c̄se</i>, <i>cēse</i> ‘cheese’ (from Latin <i>caseus</i>) + <i>holm</i> ‘piece of dry land in a fen’ and refers to a waterside meadow good for dairy farming and hence for producing cheeses. In the 14th century members of this family migrated to the Highlands, settling in Strathglass, where their name was Gaelicized as <b>Siosal</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Chisom","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  , once common in Yorkshire but now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chisam","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  , once common in Cumbria but now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chisolm","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Chisholm  ."]},{"name":"Chisum","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chislom","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Chisholm   or   Chisolm  ."]},{"name":"Chezem","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Chisholm  . Compare   Chisum  ."]},{"name":"Chism","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alexander de Chisholm Lord of Chisholme in Roxburgh and Paxtoun in Berwickshire - 4th of Chisholme was born about 1285, in Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of John de Chisholm Del Counte de Berwyke, 3rd of Chisholme. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1335, in Roxburghshire, Scotland, at the age of 52."},"et":{"Abt 1285–about 1335":"umbes 1285–umbes 1335","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1302–1386":"1302–1386","1258–1321":"1258–1321","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","1258":"1258","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1321":"1321","1386":"1386","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1285":"1285","Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Paxton, Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1285–about 1335":"noin 1285–noin 1335","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1302–1386":"1302–1386","1258–1321":"1258–1321","Abt 1285":"noin 1285","1258":"1258","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1321":"1321","1386":"1386","about 1335":"noin 1335","1285":"1285","Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Paxton, Berwickshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"Abt 1285–about 1335":"environ 1285–environ 1335","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1302–1386":"1302–1386","1258–1321":"1258–1321","Abt 1285":"environ 1285","1258":"1258","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1321":"1321","1386":"1386","about 1335":"environ 1335","1285":"1285","Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"